> - **Course:** PBCIT504 - PROGRAMMING FOR INTERNET OF THINGS
> - **Module:** Module 4
> - **Topic:** Project on Java: Bill of Materials

<!-- SECTION_1_START -->
# 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

## 1.1 Formal Definition (KTU 2024 Syllabus Terminology)

> [!NOTE]
> **Bill of Materials (BOM)** is a comprehensive, hierarchical, structured list of all raw materials, sub-assemblies, intermediate assemblies, sub-components, parts, and the quantities of each required to manufacture, install, or repair an end product. In the context of **Internet of Things (IoT)**, a BOM enumerates every sensor, actuator, microcontroller, communication module, power supply unit, wiring harness, and enclosure element required to assemble a functional IoT device.

According to the **KTU 2024 Scheme (PBCIT504 - Programming for IoT)**, the BOM is treated as a **recursive data-structure problem** that must be solved using **Object-Oriented Programming (OOP)** in Java. The syllabus explicitly asks the student to design a Java project that mirrors a real engineering BOM, demonstrating the use of:

- **Classes and Objects** (modelling components and assemblies)
- **Inheritance** (generic `Component` → specialized `Sensor`, `Actuator`, `IC`)
- **Composition / Aggregation** (a `Product` is composed of sub-assemblies)
- **Collections Framework** (`ArrayList`, `HashMap`, `TreeMap`)
- **File I/O / Serialization** (persisting the BOM)
- **Swing / JavaFX GUI** (visualizing the BOM tree)
- **JDBC / MySQL** (optional backend persistence)

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Key KTU Terminology (verbatim from syllabus):**
> - **Level 0 (Top-Level BOM):** Final product only.
> - **Level 1 BOM:** Top product + its immediate sub-assemblies.
> - **Multi-Level BOM (Indented BOM):** Recursive explosion to every leaf component.
> - **Phantom BOM:** A sub-assembly that exists only virtually, never stocked.
> - **Cost Roll-Up:** The recursive aggregation of cost from leaves to root.

---

## 1.2 Conceptual Analogy / Intuition

> [!TIP]
> **Plain-English Analogy — "The Smart Kitchen Recipe"**
>
> Imagine you are baking a **wedding cake** for 200 guests. The cake itself is the **Product**. The recipe you write down is the **Bill of Materials**. But notice: the cake is not made of raw flour directly — it is made of *tiers*, and each tier is made of *sponge layers*, and each sponge layer is made of *ingredients*. A BOM captures **every level** of this nesting.
>
> - **Level 0:** Wedding Cake (200 servings)
> - **Level 1:** 3 Cake Tiers (Bottom 100, Middle 60, Top 40)
> - **Level 2:** Each tier → Sponge + Cream + Decoration
> - **Level 3 (Leaf):** Sponge → 500 g flour, 8 eggs, 200 g sugar...
>
> Now apply this to an **IoT Smart Weather Station**:
> - **Level 0:** Smart Weather Station
> - **Level 1:** Sensor Module, Processor Module, Communication Module, Power Module
> - **Level 2 (Leaf):** DHT22 sensor, ESP32 chip, ESP8266 WiFi module, 5V Li-Po battery, jumper wires...

This is exactly the structure a Java BOM project must represent — a **tree where every node is either a sub-assembly (with children) or a leaf component (with quantity and cost)**.

---

## 1.3 Physical Constants and Standard Metrics in BOM

The following standard engineering metrics are used throughout any BOM system:

- **Bill Unit of Measure (UOM):** *each (ea)*, *grams (g)*, *meters (m)*, *liters (L)*
- **Standard Cost:** *INR (₹)* or *USD ($)* per unit
- **Lead Time:** *days* — time to procure one unit
- **Shrinkage Factor (Yield Loss):** typically **2 % to 5 %** in electronics manufacturing
- **Safety Stock Multiplier:** usually **1.10× to 1.25×** of calculated quantity
- **Effective Cost Margin:** commonly **15 % to 30 %** for IoT hardware BOMs

> [!NOTE]
> In KTU exam answers, any of the above metrics, when cited, must be written in **bold** and accompanied by their unit symbol to earn full marks.

<!-- SECTION_1_END -->

<!-- SECTION_2_START -->
# 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

## 2.1 Theoretical Foundations

The Bill of Materials is fundamentally a **recursive tree data structure** (a rooted, acyclic graph where each node has zero or more children). In Java, this is naturally mapped onto **Object Composition** — the principle that *"a Product has-a Component, and a Component may have-a sub-Component"*.

### 2.1.1 The Core Logical Steps in BOM Construction

1. **Identification:** Enumerate every part of the final product (top-down decomposition).
2. **Classification:** Mark each item as a *raw component (leaf)* or an *assembly (intermediate node)*.
3. **Quantification:** Attach a quantity `qᵢ` to every edge (parent → child).
4. **Cost Attribution:** Attach a unit cost `cᵢ` to every leaf node.
5. **Cost Roll-Up (Bottom-Up Aggregation):** Recursively compute the cost of every assembly.
6. **Explosion (Top-Down Traversal):** Recursively flatten the tree to produce an indented multi-level BOM report.
7. **Persistence:** Write the tree to disk (serialization) or to a relational database (JDBC).
8. **Visualization:** Render the tree using Swing's `JTree` component.

### 2.1.2 The "Why" Behind Each Step

- **Identification** is necessary because IoT devices have **heterogeneous parts** (electronic, mechanical, packaging) that must be sourced differently.
- **Classification** enables **recursion**: leaves terminate the recursion, assemblies continue it.
- **Quantification** matters because procurement is done in **bulk**, not piece-by-piece.
- **Cost Roll-Up** is what allows the manufacturer to know the **true landed cost** of a product *before* production begins.
- **Explosion** is what gives the **shop floor** the flat list of parts they need to pick.
- **Persistence** allows the BOM to be shared across teams (design, procurement, manufacturing).
- **Visualization** is what makes the BOM **human-readable** for non-technical stakeholders.

---

## 2.2 KTU Formula Sheet / Cheat Sheet

> [!IMPORTANT]
> The following table is the **complete formula sheet** you must memorize for any KTU exam question involving BOM cost calculations. The vertical bar `|` is intentionally replaced with `\vert` to keep the markdown table valid.

| **#** | **Formula** | **Description** | **Unit** |
| :---: | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| 1 | $Q_{\text{eff}} = \lceil q \times (1 + s) \rceil$ | Effective procurement quantity including shrinkage $s$ (decimal, e.g. 0.03) | *ea* |
| 2 | $Q_{\text{safe}} = \lceil Q_{\text{eff}} \times k \rceil$ | Safety-stocked quantity, $k \in \left[1.10,\ 1.25\right]$ | *ea* |
| 3 | $C_{\text{leaf}} = c \times q$ | Cost contribution of a single leaf component | ₹ or \$ |
| 4 | $C_{\text{assembly}} = \sum_{i=1}^{n} C_{\text{child},i}$ | Recursive roll-up of an assembly's cost | ₹ or \$ |
| 5 | $C_{\text{total}} = C_{\text{assembly, root}}$ | Total product cost (roll-up to root) | ₹ or \$ |
| 6 | $C_{\text{landed}} = C_{\text{total}} \times (1 + m_{\text{tax}} + m_{\text{ship}})$ | Landed cost including tax + shipping margin | ₹ or \$ |
| 7 | $C_{\text{sell}} = C_{\text{landed}} \times (1 + p)$ | Selling price, where $p$ is the profit margin (e.g. 0.25) | ₹ or \$ |
| 8 | $T_{\text{critical}} = \max_{i \in \text{path}} \left( L_{i} \right)$ | Critical-path lead time, $L_i$ = lead time of part $i$ | *days* |
| 9 | $W_{\text{count}} = \sum_{v \in \text{tree}} 1$ | Total part count (every node counted once) | *ea* |
| 10 | $E_{\text{flat}} = \sum_{l \in \text{leaves}} 1$ | Flat-exploded line-item count | *ea* |

Where:
- $q$ = per-assembly quantity of a child
- $s$ = shrinkage / yield-loss fraction (e.g. **0.03** = 3 %)
- $k$ = safety-stock multiplier (typical **1.10 to 1.25**)
- $c$ = unit cost of one leaf
- $m_{\text{tax}}$, $m_{\text{ship}}$ = tax and shipping margins (fractions)
- $p$ = profit margin (fraction)
- $L_i$ = procurement lead time of part $i$

---

## 2.3 Real-World Engineering Utility

> [!TIP]
> The BOM is the **single most important document** in any manufacturing industry. In IoT product companies (e.g., **Espressif, Bosch, Texas Instruments, Honeywell**), the BOM drives:
> - **Procurement decisions** (which vendor, what quantity, when to order)
> - **PCB design verification** (each BOM line must match a footprint on the PCB)
> - **Cost engineering** (every ₹1 saved on a ₹500 BOM = 5 % margin gain when sold at ₹1,000)
> - **Regulatory compliance** (BOM must list RoHS-compliant parts for EU sales)
> - **Software bill of materials (SBOM)** — the same concept applied to software dependencies in IoT firmware

In the KTU lab exam, the Java BOM project is the **single largest program** students write, often worth **40–60 marks** in the internal evaluation.

<!-- SECTION_2_END -->

<!-- SECTION_3_START -->
# 3. Step-by-Step Derivation, Class Design & Analytical Matrix

## 3.1 Worked Numerical Example (Cost Roll-Up Derivation)

**Problem:** A Smart Weather Station (Product P) is assembled as follows. Compute the **total effective cost** including **5 % yield loss**, **15 % safety stock**, and **18 % GST**.

- 1 × Sensor Module
  - 1 × DHT22 Sensor @ ₹450
  - 1 × BMP280 Sensor @ ₹320
  - 1 × Rain-Gauge Reed Switch @ ₹180
- 1 × Processor Module
  - 1 × ESP32-WROOM-32 @ ₹350
  - 1 × 16 MB SPI Flash @ ₹90
  - 1 × Crystal Oscillator 40 MHz @ ₹25
- 1 × Communication Module
  - 1 × SIM800L GSM Module @ ₹780
  - 1 × SMA Antenna @ ₹120
- 1 × Power Module
  - 1 × Li-Po 3.7 V 2000 mAh @ ₹550
  - 1 × TP4056 Charging IC @ ₹35
  - 1 × AMS1117-3.3V LDO @ ₹25
- 1 × IP65 Enclosure @ ₹420
- 4 × M3 Mounting Screws @ ₹5 each

### Step 1 — Identify every leaf and its unit cost

Leaves (Level-3 of the BOM tree) and their per-unit cost $c$:

| **Leaf** | **c (₹)** | **q (per Product P)** |
| :--- | :---: | :---: |
| DHT22 | 450 | 1 |
| BMP280 | 320 | 1 |
| Rain-Gauge Reed Switch | 180 | 1 |
| ESP32-WROOM-32 | 350 | 1 |
| 16 MB SPI Flash | 90 | 1 |
| Crystal Oscillator | 25 | 1 |
| SIM800L | 780 | 1 |
| SMA Antenna | 120 | 1 |
| Li-Po 2000 mAh | 550 | 1 |
| TP4056 | 35 | 1 |
| AMS1117-3.3V | 25 | 1 |
| IP65 Enclosure | 420 | 1 |
| M3 Screw | 5 | 4 |

### Step 2 — Apply shrinkage and safety-stock

For each leaf, $Q_{\text{safe}} = \lceil q \times (1 + s) \times k \rceil$ with $s = 0.05$ and $k = 1.15$.

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Factor} &= (1 + 0.05) \times 1.15 \\
&= 1.05 \times 1.15 \\
&= 1.2075
\end{aligned}
$$

For the M3 Screw ($q = 4$):

$$
\begin{aligned}
Q_{\text{safe}} &= \lceil 4 \times 1.2075 \rceil \\
&= \lceil 4.83 \rceil \\
&= 5
\end{aligned}
$$

For all $q = 1$ items: $Q_{\text{safe}} = \lceil 1.2075 \rceil = 2$.

### Step 3 — Compute leaf cost

$$
\begin{aligned}
C_{\text{leaf, DHT22}} &= 2 \times 450 = \text{₹ } 900 \\
C_{\text{leaf, BMP280}} &= 2 \times 320 = \text{₹ } 640 \\
C_{\text{leaf, Reed}}   &= 2 \times 180 = \text{₹ } 360 \\
C_{\text{leaf, ESP32}} &= 2 \times 350 = \text{₹ } 700 \\
C_{\text{leaf, Flash}} &= 2 \times 90  = \text{₹ } 180 \\
C_{\text{leaf, XO}}    &= 2 \times 25  = \text{₹ } 50 \\
C_{\text{leaf, SIM800L}} &= 2 \times 780 = \text{₹ } 1560 \\
C_{\text{leaf, ANT}}   &= 2 \times 120 = \text{₹ } 240 \\
C_{\text{leaf, BAT}}   &= 2 \times 550 = \text{₹ } 1100 \\
C_{\text{leaf, TP4056}}&= 2 \times 35  = \text{₹ } 70 \\
C_{\text{leaf, LDO}}   &= 2 \times 25  = \text{₹ } 50 \\
C_{\text{leaf, ENC}}   &= 2 \times 420 = \text{₹ } 840 \\
C_{\text{leaf, Screw}} &= 5 \times 5   = \text{₹ } 25
\end{aligned}
$$

### Step 4 — Recursive assembly roll-up

$$
\begin{aligned}
C_{\text{Sensor Module}} &= 900 + 640 + 360 = \text{₹ } 1900 \\
C_{\text{Processor Module}} &= 700 + 180 + 50 = \text{₹ } 930 \\
C_{\text{Comm Module}}   &= 1560 + 240 = \text{₹ } 1800 \\
C_{\text{Power Module}}  &= 1100 + 70 + 50 = \text{₹ } 1220
\end{aligned}
$$

### Step 5 — Total Product Cost (roll-up to root)

$$
\begin{aligned}
C_{\text{total}} &= C_{\text{Sensor}} + C_{\text{Processor}} + C_{\text{Comm}} + C_{\text{Power}} + C_{\text{Enclosure}} + C_{\text{Screws}} \\
&= 1900 + 930 + 1800 + 1220 + 840 + 25 \\
&= \text{₹ } 6715
\end{aligned}
$$

### Step 6 — Add GST (18 %)

$$
\begin{aligned}
C_{\text{landed}} &= 6715 \times (1 + 0.18) \\
&= 6715 \times 1.18 \\
&= \text{₹ } 7923.70
\end{aligned}
$$

### Step 7 — Add 25 % profit margin for selling price

$$
\begin{aligned}
C_{\text{sell}} &= 7923.70 \times 1.25 \\
&= \text{₹ } 9904.625 \\
&\approx \text{₹ } 9905
\end{aligned}
$$

> [!NOTE]
> **Result:** One unit of the Smart Weather Station has a procurement cost of **₹ 6,715**, a landed cost of **₹ 7,923.70**, and a recommended retail price of **₹ 9,905**.

---

## 3.2 Complete Java Project: Bill of Materials (IoT)

Below is the **complete, compilable Java project** with five source files. Each file is presented in full, with no truncation.

### 3.2.1 File 1 — `Component.java` (Abstract Leaf/Assembly Base Class)

```java
/**
 * PBCIT504 - Programming for Internet of Things
 * Module 4 - Project on Java: Bill of Materials
 * File: Component.java
 * Author: KTU 2024 Scheme Reference Implementation
 *
 * Abstract base class representing any node in the BOM tree.
 * A Component is EITHER a leaf (raw part) OR an assembly (has children).
 * Implemented using the Composite Design Pattern.
 */
import java.io.Serializable;
import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.List;

public abstract class Component implements Serializable {
    private static final long serialVersionUID = 1L;

    // ---------- Identity Fields ----------
    protected String partNumber;        // e.g. "ESP32-WROOM-32"
    protected String description;       // e.g. "Dual-core WiFi+BT MCU"
    protected int quantity;             // q: how many of this per parent
    protected double unitCost;          // c: cost of ONE unit (₹)
    protected String unitOfMeasure;     // UOM: "ea", "g", "m"
    protected int leadTimeDays;         // procurement lead time
    protected List<Component> children; // sub-components (empty if leaf)

    // ---------- Constructor ----------
    public Component(String partNumber, String description,
                     int quantity, double unitCost,
                     String unitOfMeasure, int leadTimeDays) {
        this.partNumber    = partNumber;
        this.description   = description;
        this.quantity      = quantity;
        this.unitCost      = unitCost;
        this.unitOfMeasure = unitOfMeasure;
        this.leadTimeDays  = leadTimeDays;
        this.children      = new ArrayList<Component>();
    }

    // ---------- Getters / Setters ----------
    public String getPartNumber()         { return partNumber; }
    public String getDescription()        { return description; }
    public int    getQuantity()           { return quantity; }
    public double getUnitCost()           { return unitCost; }
    public String getUnitOfMeasure()      { return unitOfMeasure; }
    public int    getLeadTimeDays()       { return leadTimeDays; }
    public List<Component> getChildren()  { return children; }

    public void setQuantity(int quantity)    { this.quantity = quantity; }
    public void setUnitCost(double unitCost) { this.unitCost = unitCost; }
    public void setLeadTimeDays(int days)    { this.leadTimeDays = days; }

    // ---------- Tree Manipulation ----------
    public void addChild(Component child) {
        this.children.add(child);
    }

    public void removeChild(Component child) {
        this.children.remove(child);
    }

    // ---------- Composite Pattern Methods ----------
    public boolean isLeaf() {
        return this.children.isEmpty();
    }

    /**
     * Recursive cost roll-up.
     * Leaf: cost = unitCost * quantity
     * Assembly: cost = sum of all children's rolled-up cost
     */
    public double getRolledUpCost() {
        if (isLeaf()) {
            return unitCost * quantity;
        } else {
            double total = 0.0;
            for (Component c : children) {
                total += c.getRolledUpCost();
            }
            return total;
        }
    }

    /**
     * Effective procurement quantity including shrinkage + safety stock.
     */
    public int getEffectiveQuantity(double shrinkage, double safetyMultiplier) {
        double eff = quantity * (1.0 + shrinkage) * safetyMultiplier;
        return (int) Math.ceil(eff);
    }

    /**
     * Recursive top-down explosion returning a flat list of all leaves.
     */
    public void explode(java.util.List<Component> accumulator) {
        if (isLeaf()) {
            accumulator.add(this);
        } else {
            for (Component c : children) {
                c.explode(accumulator);
            }
        }
    }

    /**
     * Critical-path lead time = max of all leaves' lead times.
     */
    public int getCriticalLeadTime() {
        if (isLeaf()) {
            return leadTimeDays;
        } else {
            int max = 0;
            for (Component c : children) {
                int childLead = c.getCriticalLeadTime();
                if (childLead > max) max = childLead;
            }
            return max;
        }
    }

    /**
     * Pretty-print the BOM tree with indentation.
     */
    public void printBOM(int depth) {
        StringBuilder indent = new StringBuilder();
        for (int i = 0; i < depth; i++) indent.append("  ");
        System.out.printf("%s[%d x] %s  %s  Rs.%.2f  (Lead: %d d)%n",
                indent.toString(), quantity, partNumber,
                description, unitCost, leadTimeDays);
        for (Component c : children) {
            c.printBOM(depth + 1);
        }
    }

    // Each subclass must implement its own category tag
    public abstract String getCategory();
}
```

### 3.2.2 File 2 — `LeafPart.java` (Concrete Leaf Class)

```java
/**
 * Concrete leaf: a raw, indivisible part (e.g. resistor, screw, IC chip).
 */
public class LeafPart extends Component {

    private String manufacturer;     // e.g. "Texas Instruments"
    private String datasheetURL;     // hyperlink to datasheet

    public LeafPart(String partNumber, String description,
                    int quantity, double unitCost,
                    String unitOfMeasure, int leadTimeDays,
                    String manufacturer, String datasheetURL) {
        super(partNumber, description, quantity, unitCost,
              unitOfMeasure, leadTimeDays);
        this.manufacturer = manufacturer;
        this.datasheetURL = datasheetURL;
    }

    public String getManufacturer() { return manufacturer; }
    public String getDatasheetURL() { return datasheetURL; }

    @Override
    public String getCategory() {
        return "LEAF";
    }
}
```

### 3.2.3 File 3 — `Assembly.java` (Concrete Composite Class)

```java
/**
 * Concrete composite: an assembly composed of other components.
 * Examples: "Sensor Module", "Power Module", "Smart Weather Station".
 */
public class Assembly extends Component {

    private String revisionNumber;     // e.g. "Rev-C"
    private String designedBy;         // e.g. "KTU IoT Lab"

    public Assembly(String partNumber, String description,
                    int quantity, double unitCost,
                    String unitOfMeasure, int leadTimeDays,
                    String revisionNumber, String designedBy) {
        super(partNumber, description, quantity, unitCost,
              unitOfMeasure, leadTimeDays);
        this.revisionNumber = revisionNumber;
        this.designedBy     = designedBy;
    }

    public String getRevisionNumber() { return revisionNumber; }
    public String getDesignedBy()     { return designedBy; }

    @Override
    public String getCategory() {
        return "ASSEMBLY";
    }
}
```

### 3.2.4 File 4 — `BOMRepository.java` (Persistence Layer)

```java
/**
 * Saves / loads a BOM tree to/from a binary file using Java Serialization.
 */
import java.io.FileInputStream;
import java.io.FileOutputStream;
import java.io.ObjectInputStream;
import java.io.ObjectOutputStream;

public class BOMRepository {

    public static void saveToFile(Component root, String filePath)
            throws Exception {
        ObjectOutputStream oos = new ObjectOutputStream(
                new FileOutputStream(filePath));
        oos.writeObject(root);
        oos.close();
    }

    @SuppressWarnings("unchecked")
    public static Component loadFromFile(String filePath)
            throws Exception {
        ObjectInputStream ois = new ObjectInputStream(
                new FileInputStream(filePath));
        Component root = (Component) ois.readObject();
        ois.close();
        return root;
    }

    /**
     * Export the flat exploded BOM to a CSV file (Excel-friendly).
     */
    public static void exportToCSV(Component root, String csvPath)
            throws Exception {
        java.io.PrintWriter pw = new java.io.PrintWriter(
                new java.io.FileWriter(csvPath));
        pw.println("PartNumber,Description,Quantity,UnitCost,UOM,LeadTimeDays,Category");
        java.util.List<Component> flat = new java.util.ArrayList<Component>();
        root.explode(flat);
        for (Component c : flat) {
            pw.printf("%s,%s,%d,%.2f,%s,%d,%s%n",
                    c.getPartNumber(), c.getDescription(),
                    c.getQuantity(), c.getUnitCost(),
                    c.getUnitOfMeasure(), c.getLeadTimeDays(),
                    c.getCategory());
        }
        pw.close();
    }
}
```

### 3.2.5 File 5 — `BOMDemo.java` (Main Driver — Builds and Demonstrates the IoT BOM)

```java
/**
 * PBCIT504 - Main demo: builds a Smart Weather Station BOM tree
 * and demonstrates roll-up, explosion, persistence, and CSV export.
 */
import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.List;

public class BOMDemo {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        // -------- LEAF COMPONENTS (Level 3) --------

        LeafPart dht22   = new LeafPart("DHT22",  "Temp+Humidity Sensor",
                1, 450, "ea", 7, "Aosong", "https://datasheet.url");
        LeafPart bmp280  = new LeafPart("BMP280", "Pressure Sensor",
                1, 320, "ea", 5, "Bosch",   "https://datasheet.url");
        LeafPart reed    = new LeafPart("REED-01","Rain Gauge Switch",
                1, 180, "ea", 10, "Generic", "https://datasheet.url");

        LeafPart esp32   = new LeafPart("ESP32-WROOM-32", "Dual-core MCU",
                1, 350, "ea", 12, "Espressif", "https://datasheet.url");
        LeafPart flash   = new LeafPart("W25Q16",  "16-Mbit SPI Flash",
                1,  90, "ea",  8, "Winbond",   "https://datasheet.url");
        LeafPart xtal    = new LeafPart("XTAL-40M","40 MHz Crystal",
                1,  25, "ea",  6, "Abracon",   "https://datasheet.url");

        LeafPart sim800l = new LeafPart("SIM800L", "GSM Modem",
                1, 780, "ea", 14, "Simcom",    "https://datasheet.url");
        LeafPart ant     = new LeafPart("SMA-ANT", "SMA Antenna",
                1, 120, "ea",  4, "Linx",      "https://datasheet.url");

        LeafPart battery = new LeafPart("LIPO-2K", "3.7V 2000mAh Battery",
                1, 550, "ea", 9, "Generic",   "https://datasheet.url");
        LeafPart tp4056  = new LeafPart("TP4056",  "Li-Ion Charger IC",
                1,  35, "ea", 5, "NanJing",   "https://datasheet.url");
        LeafPart ldo     = new LeafPart("AMS1117", "3.3V LDO Regulator",
                1,  25, "ea", 5, "Advanced",  "https://datasheet.url");

        LeafPart encl    = new LeafPart("ENC-IP65","IP65 Enclosure",
                1, 420, "ea", 11, "Hammond",   "https://datasheet.url");
        LeafPart screw   = new LeafPart("M3-8MM",  "M3 Mounting Screw",
                4,   5, "ea",  3, "Generic",   "https://datasheet.url");

        // -------- SUB-ASSEMBLIES (Level 2) --------

        Assembly sensorModule = new Assembly(
                "MOD-SENS-01", "Sensor Module", 1, 0, "ea", 10,
                "Rev-A", "KTU IoT Lab");
        sensorModule.addChild(dht22);
        sensorModule.addChild(bmp280);
        sensorModule.addChild(reed);

        Assembly procModule = new Assembly(
                "MOD-PROC-01", "Processor Module", 1, 0, "ea", 12,
                "Rev-B", "KTU IoT Lab");
        procModule.addChild(esp32);
        procModule.addChild(flash);
        procModule.addChild(xtal);

        Assembly commModule = new Assembly(
                "MOD-COMM-01", "Communication Module", 1, 0, "ea", 14,
                "Rev-A", "KTU IoT Lab");
        commModule.addChild(sim800l);
        commModule.addChild(ant);

        Assembly powerModule = new Assembly(
                "MOD-PWR-01",  "Power Module", 1, 0, "ea", 9,
                "Rev-A", "KTU IoT Lab");
        powerModule.addChild(battery);
        powerModule.addChild(tp4056);
        powerModule.addChild(ldo);

        // -------- TOP-LEVEL PRODUCT (Level 1) --------

        Assembly weatherStation = new Assembly(
                "PROD-WX-01", "Smart Weather Station", 1, 0, "ea", 14,
                "Rev-1.0", "KTU IoT Lab");
        weatherStation.addChild(sensorModule);
        weatherStation.addChild(procModule);
        weatherStation.addChild(commModule);
        weatherStation.addChild(powerModule);
        weatherStation.addChild(encl);
        weatherStation.addChild(screw);

        // -------- 1. PRINT THE BOM TREE --------

        System.out.println("===== INDENTED BOM TREE =====");
        weatherStation.printBOM(0);
        System.out.println();

        // -------- 2. COST ROLL-UP --------

        double shrinkage = 0.05;   // 5 % yield loss
        double safety    = 1.15;   // 15 % safety stock
        double gst       = 0.18;   // 18 % GST
        double margin    = 0.25;   // 25 % profit

        double rolledUp = weatherStation.getRolledUpCost();
        double landed   = rolledUp * (1.0 + gst);
        double selling  = landed * (1.0 + margin);

        System.out.printf("Raw Rolled-Up Cost : Rs. %.2f%n", rolledUp);
        System.out.printf("Landed Cost (GST)  : Rs. %.2f%n", landed);
        System.out.printf("Selling Price      : Rs. %.2f%n", selling);
        System.out.println();

        // -------- 3. EFFECTIVE QUANTITY (with shrinkage + safety) --------

        List<Component> flat = new ArrayList<Component>();
        weatherStation.explode(flat);
        System.out.println("===== EFFECTIVE PROCUREMENT QUANTITIES =====");
        for (Component c : flat) {
            int qEff = c.getEffectiveQuantity(shrinkage, safety);
            System.out.printf("%-15s  q=%d  q_eff=%d  cost=Rs.%.2f%n",
                    c.getPartNumber(), c.getQuantity(), qEff,
                    qEff * c.getUnitCost());
        }
        System.out.println();

        // -------- 4. CRITICAL LEAD TIME --------

        System.out.printf("Critical Lead Time : %d days%n",
                weatherStation.getCriticalLeadTime());
        System.out.println();

        // -------- 5. PERSISTENCE --------

        try {
            BOMRepository.saveToFile(weatherStation, "bom_weather_station.ser");
            System.out.println("[OK] BOM serialized to bom_weather_station.ser");

            BOMRepository.exportToCSV(weatherStation, "bom_weather_station.csv");
            System.out.println("[OK] BOM exported to bom_weather_station.csv");
        } catch (Exception e) {
            System.err.println("Persistence error: " + e.getMessage());
        }
    }
}
```

