## 5.1 Part A — 3-Mark Questions

> **Q1. `[KTU University Exam – Dec 2023]`** Define the term **Bill of Materials (BOM)** as applied to an IoT product. Mention any two software-engineering design patterns that a Java BOM project typically uses.

**Model Answer (3 marks):**
A **Bill of Materials (BOM)** is a structured, hierarchical list of every raw material, sub-assembly, intermediate part, and quantity required to manufacture an end IoT product. Each entry typically carries a part number, description, quantity, unit of measure, unit cost, and lead time. In a Java implementation, two design patterns are almost always used:
1. **Composite Design Pattern** — treats individual objects (leaves) and compositions (assemblies) uniformly through a common `Component` interface.
2. **Repository / DAO Pattern** — abstracts persistence (file or database) behind a `BOMRepository` class so the in-memory tree is decoupled from storage.

*(1 mark for definition, 1 mark each for the two patterns.)*

---

> **Q2. `[KTU University Exam – May 2024]`** Differentiate between a **single-level BOM** and a **multi-level BOM** with a suitable IoT example.

**Model Answer (3 marks):**
A **single-level BOM** lists only the immediate child components of a product without further decomposition. For example, for a Smart Weather Station, it would only list *Sensor Module, Processor Module, Communication Module, Power Module, Enclosure* — but not the chips inside those modules.
A **multi-level BOM (Indented BOM)** recursively explodes every sub-assembly to the leaf level. For the same product, it would further list *DHT22, BMP280, ESP32, W25Q16, SIM800L, TP4056*, etc., and any sub-sub-parts they may have.
Single-level BOMs are quick to read but cannot drive procurement; multi-level BOMs are essential for **procurement, cost roll-up, and manufacturing**.

*(1.5 marks each for the two definitions + example.)*

